			<h2>Instructions</h2>
<p><strong>To calculate the number of days between any two dates such as in=
 computing in-custody credits (i.e. the left-hand calculator above):</stron=
g></p>
<dl>
<dt>Step 1 =E2=80=93 Choose your starting date.</dt>
<dd>Select the starting date of your choice using the drop-down arrows next=
 to each selection box. When you open the Day Calculator, the date is autom=
atically set to today=E2=80=99s date. As the calculator takes today=E2=80=
=99s date from your system clock, it is important to make sure that your sy=
stem date is correctly set for this function to work properly.</dd>
<dt>Step 2 =E2=80=93 Choose your ending date.</dt>
<dd>Select the ending date of your choice using the drop-down arrows next t=
o each selection box. When you open the Day Calculator, the date is automat=
ically set to today=E2=80=99s date. As the calculator takes today=E2=80=99s=
 date from your system clock, it is important to make sure that your system=
 date is correctly set for this function to work properly.</dd>
<dt>Step 3 =E2=80=93 Calculate.</dt>
<dd>Press the button marked =E2=80=9CCalculate=E2=80=9D to carry out the ca=
lculation. The number of days difference will be displayed at the bottom of=
 the form. Note that the calculation <em>includes</em> the starting date it=
self (i.e. day number 1 is the day you enter as your starting date) AND <em=
>includes</em> the ending date (i.e. the day you enter as your ending date)=
.</dd>
</dl>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>To add or subtract a chosen number of days to or from any date a=
s in computing some due dates (i.e. the right-hand calculator above):</stro=
ng></p>
<dl>
<dt>Step 1 =E2=80=93 Choose your starting date.</dt>
<dd>Select the starting date of your choice using the drop-down arrows next=
 to each selection box. When you open the Day Calculator, the date is autom=
atically set to today=E2=80=99s date. As the calculator takes today=E2=80=
=99s date from your system clock, it is important to make sure that your sy=
stem date is correctly set for this function to work properly.</dd>
<dt>Step 2 =E2=80=93 Choose whether to add or subtract.</dt>
<dd>Either select the radio button marked =E2=80=9CAdd=E2=80=9D or the radi=
o button marked =E2=80=9CSubtract=E2=80=9D.</dd>
<dt>Step 3 =E2=80=93 Type in the number of days to add or subtract.</dt>
<dd>This must be a whole number.</dd>
<dt>Step 4 =E2=80=93 Calculate.</dt>
<dd>Press the button marked =E2=80=9CCalculate=E2=80=9D to carry out the ca=
lculation. The new ending date will be displayed at the bottom of the form,=
 including the day of the week. Note that the calculation <em>excludes</em>=
 the starting date itself (ie. day number 1 is the day <em>after</em> your =
starting date) but <em>includes</em> the ending date.</dd>
</dl>
<p><a class=3D"backtop" href=3D"https://capcentral.org/resources/charts_cal=
cs/datecalc/#top">BACK TO TOP</a></p>

